SENATE BILL 24
J1 6lr0223
(PRE–FILED) CF HB 276
By: Chair, Education, Energy, and the Environment Committee (By Request –
Departmental – Maryland Institute for Emergency Medical Services
Systems)
Requested: September 30, 2025
Introduced and read first time: January 14, 2026
Assigned to: Education, Energy, and the Environment
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted
Read second time: February 20, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 State Emergency Medical Services Board – Public Access Automated External
3 Defibrillator Program – Revisions
4 FOR the purpose of altering the Public Access Automated External Defibrillator Program,
5 including by establishing requirements regarding an automated external
6 defibrillator (AED) coordinator, repealing certain provisions of law regarding
7 regional council AED committees, and exempting certain law enforcement agencies
8 from being required to obtain a certificate for an AED deployed in a patrol vehicle of
9 the law enforcement agency; establishing certain certification qualifications for
10 grocery stores and restaurants under the Program; and generally relating to the
11 Public Access Automated External Defibrillator Program.
12 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
13 Article – Education
14 Section 13–517
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
18 Article – Health – General
19 Section 21–330.3(c)
20 Annotated Code of Maryland
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0024*

2 SENATE BILL 24
1 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
2 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
3 Article – Public Safety
4 Section 2–101(a) and (g)
5 Annotated Code of Maryland
6 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
7 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
8 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
9 Article – Education
10 13–517.
11 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
12 (2) “AED COORDINATOR” MEANS THE INDIVIDUAL DESIGNATED BY A
13 REGISTERED ENTITY TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE WITH THE REQUIREMENTS OF THIS
14 SECTION.
15 [(2)] (3) “Automated external defibrillator (AED)” means a medical heart
16 monitor and defibrillator device that:
17 (i) Is cleared for market by the [federal] U.S. Food and Drug
18 Administration;
19 (ii) Recognizes the presence or absence of ventricular fibrillation or
20 rapid ventricular tachycardia;
21 (iii) Determines, without intervention by an operator, whether
22 defibrillation should be performed;
23 (iv) On determining that defibrillation should be performed,
24 automatically charges; and
25 (v) 1. Requires operator intervention to deliver the electrical
26 impulse; or
27 2. Automatically continues with delivery of electrical
28 impulse.
29 [(3)] (4) “Certificate” means a certificate issued by the EMS Board to a
30 registered [facility] ENTITY.

SENATE BILL 24 3
1 [(4) (i)] (5) [“Facility”] “ENTITY” means AN ORGANIZATION, A
2 BUSINESS, AN ASSOCIATION, an agency, [an association,] a corporation, a firm, OR a
3 partnership[, or any other entity] IN THE STATE.
4 [(ii) “Facility” does not include a grocery store or restaurant that is
5 subject to § 21–330.3 of the Health – General Article.]
6 [(5)] (6) “Jurisdictional emergency medical services operational program”
7 means the institution, agency, corporation, or other entity that has been approved by the
8 EMS Board to provide oversight of emergency medical services for each of the local
9 government and State and federal emergency medical services programs.
10 (7) “LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN §
11 2–101 OF THE PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE.
12 [(6)] (8) “Program” means the Public Access Automated External
13 Defibrillator Program.
14 [(7) “Regional administrator” means the individual employed by the
15 Institute as regional administrator in each EMS region.
16 (8) “Regional council” means an EMS advisory body as created by the Code
17 of Maryland Regulations 30.05.
18 (9) “Regional council AED committee” means a committee appointed by the
19 regional council consisting of:
20 (i) The regional medical director;
21 (ii) The regional administrator; and
22 (iii) Three or more individuals with knowledge of and expertise in
23 AEDs.]
24 [(10)] (9) “Registered [facility”] ENTITY” means an [organization, a
25 business association, an agency, or any other] entity that meets the requirements of the
26 EMS Board for registering with the Program.
27 (b) (1) There is a Public Access Automated External Defibrillator Program.
28 (2) The purpose of the Program is to:
29 (i) Coordinate an effective statewide public access defibrillation
30 program; and

4 SENATE BILL 24
1 (ii) Implement the initiative to co–locate naloxone with automated
2 external defibrillators placed in public buildings, as required under § 13–518 of this
3 subtitle.
4 (3) The Program shall be administered by the EMS Board.
5 (c) The EMS Board may:
6 (1) Adopt regulations for the administration of the Program;
7 (2) Issue and renew certificates to [facilities] ENTITIES that meet the
8 requirements of this section;
9 (3) Deny, suspend, revoke, or refuse to renew the certificate of a registered
10 [facility] ENTITY for failure to meet the requirements of this section;
11 (4) Approve educational and training programs required under this section
12 that:
13 (i) Are conducted by any private or public entity; AND
14 (ii) [Include training in cardiopulmonary resuscitation and
15 automated external defibrillation; and
16 (iii)] May include courses from nationally recognized [entities]
17 ORGANIZATIONS such as the American Heart Association, the American Red Cross, and
18 the National Safety Council; AND
19 [(5) Approve the protocol for the use of an AED; and]
20 [(6)] (5) Delegate to the Institute any portion of its authority under this
21 section.
22 (d) (1) [Each facility] EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN PARAGRAPH (3) OF THIS
23 SUBSECTION, EACH ENTITY that desires to make automated external defibrillation
24 available shall possess a valid certificate from the EMS Board.
25 (2) This subsection does not apply to:
26 (i) A jurisdictional emergency medical services operational
27 program;
28 (ii) A licensed commercial ambulance service;
29 (iii) A health care facility as defined in § 19–114 of the
30 Health – General Article; or

SENATE BILL 24 5
1 (iv) A place of business for health care practitioners who are licensed
2 as dentists under Title 4 of the Health Occupations Article or as physicians under Title 14
3 of the Health Occupations Article and are authorized to use an AED in accordance with
4 that license.
5 (3) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY MAY NOT BE REQUIRED TO OBTAIN
6 A CERTIFICATE FOR AN AED DEPLOYED IN A PATROL VEHICLE OF THE LAW
7 ENFORCEMENT AGENCY.
8 (e) (1) To EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS
9 SUBSECTION, TO qualify for AND RETAIN a certificate [a facility] AN ENTITY shall:
10 (1) (I) [Comply with the written protocol approved by the EMS Board]
11 HAVE A WRITTEN PLAN for the use of an AED [which] THAT includes [notification of] A
12 REQUIREMENT THAT THE ENTITY NOTIFY the emergency medical services system
13 through the use of the 911 universal emergency access number as soon as possible on the
14 use of an AED;
15 (2) (II) Have established [automated external defibrillator] AED
16 maintenance, placement, operation, AND reporting[, and quality improvement] procedures
17 as required by the EMS Board;
18 (3) (III) [Maintain] REQUIRE THE AED COORDINATOR TO MAINTAIN
19 THE FUNCTIONALITY OF each AED and all related equipment and supplies in accordance
20 with the standards established by the device manufacturer and the [federal] U.S. Food
21 and Drug Administration;
22 [(4) Ensure that each individual who is expected to operate an AED for the
23 registered facility has successfully completed an educational training course and refresher
24 training as required by the EMS Board; and]
25 (4) (IV) REQUIRE THE AED COORDINATOR TO PROMOTE
26 AWARENESS OF THE LOCATION AND OPERATION OF THE AED AMONG POTENTIAL
27 OR FORESEEABLE AED OPERATORS IN CASE OF EMERGENCY; AND
28 (5) (V) If the [facility] ENTITY is a public building, meet any
29 requirements established under § 13–518 of this subtitle relating to the co–location of
30 naloxone with each AED maintained [in] BY the [facility] ENTITY.
31 (2) FOR AN ENTITY THAT IS A GROCERY STORE OR RESTAURANT, TO
32 QUALIFY FOR AND RETAIN A CERTIFICATE, THE ENTITY SHALL:
33 (I) REGISTER THE NAME OF THE ENTITY WITH THE PROGRAM;
34 AND

6 SENATE BILL 24
1 (II) MAINTAIN THE FUNCTIONALITY OF EACH AED AND ALL
2 RELATED EQUIPMENT AND SUPPLIES IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE STANDARDS
3 ESTABLISHED BY THE DEVICE MANUFACTURER AND THE U.S. FOOD AND DRUG
4 ADMINISTRATION.
5 (f) IN ADDITION TO THE REQUIREMENTS ESTABLISHED IN THIS SECTION,
6 AN ENTITY OTHER THAN A GROCERY STORE OR RESTAURANT THAT IS SUBJECT TO §
7 21–330.3 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE SHALL ENSURE THAT THE AED
8 COORDINATOR HAS SUCCESSFULLY COMPLETED AN EDUCATIONAL TRAINING
9 COURSE AND ANY REFRESHER TRAINING COURSES AS REQUIRED BY THE EMS
10 BOARD.
11 (G) A registered [facility] ENTITY shall report the use of an AED to the Institute
12 [for review by the regional council AED committee] USING THE FORM PROVIDED BY THE
13 INSTITUTE.
14 [(g)] (H) [A facility] AN ENTITY that desires to [establish] OBTAIN or renew a
15 certificate shall:
16 (1) Submit an application on the form that the EMS Board requires; and
17 (2) Meet the requirements under this section.
18 [(h)] (I) (1) The EMS Board shall issue a new or a renewed certificate to [a
19 facility] AN ENTITY that meets the requirements of this section.
20 (2) Each certificate shall include:
21 (i) The type of certificate;
22 (ii) The full name and address of the [facility] ENTITY;
23 (iii) A unique identification number; and
24 (iv) The dates of issuance and expiration of the certificate.
25 (3) A certificate is valid for 3 years.
26 [(i)] (J) The EMS Board may issue a cease and desist order or obtain injunctive
27 relief if [a facility] AN ENTITY makes automated external defibrillation available in
28 violation of this section.

SENATE BILL 24 7
1 [(j)] (K) (1) In addition to any other immunities available under statutory or
2 common law, a registered [facility] ENTITY is not civilly liable for any act or omission in
3 the provision of automated external defibrillation if the registered [facility] ENTITY:
4 (i) Has satisfied the requirements for making [automated external
5 defibrillation] AN AED available under this section; and
6 (ii) Possesses a valid certificate at the time of the act or omission.
7 [(2) In addition to any other immunities available under statutory or
8 common law, a member of the regional council AED committee is not civilly liable for any
9 act or omission in the provision of automated external defibrillation.]
10 [(3)] (2) In addition to any other immunities available under statutory or
11 common law, an individual is not civilly liable for any act or omission if:
12 (i) The individual is acting in good faith while rendering automated
13 external defibrillation to a person who is a victim or reasonably believed by the individual
14 to be a victim of a sudden cardiac arrest;
15 (ii) The assistance or aid is provided in a reasonably prudent
16 manner; and
17 (iii) The automated external defibrillation is provided without fee or
18 other compensation.
19 [(4)] (3) The immunities in this subsection are not available if the conduct
20 of the registered [facility] ENTITY or an individual amounts to gross negligence, willful or
21 wanton misconduct, or intentionally tortious conduct.
22 [(5)] (4) This subsection does not affect, and may not be construed as
23 affecting, any immunities from civil or criminal liability or defenses established by any
24 other provision of the Code or by common law to which a registered [facility, a member of
25 the regional council AED committee,] ENTITY or an individual may be entitled.
26 [(k)] (L) (1) A registered [facility] ENTITY aggrieved by a decision of the
27 Institute acting under the delegated authority of the EMS Board under this section shall
28 be afforded an opportunity for a hearing before the EMS Board.
29 (2) A registered [facility] ENTITY aggrieved by a decision of the EMS
30 Board under this section shall be afforded an opportunity for a hearing in accordance with
31 Title 10, Subtitle 2 of the State Government Article.
32 Article – Health – General
33 21–330.3.

8 SENATE BILL 24
1 (c) [Beginning January 1, 2025, each] EACH owner and operator of a grocery
2 store or restaurant shall:
3 (1) Place an automated external defibrillator in a prominent area,
4 accessible to employees and customers; and
5 [(2) Maintain the functionality of the automated external defibrillator.;
6 AND]
7 (2) (3) COMPLY WITH THE APPLICABLE REQUIREMENTS OF THE
8 PUBLIC ACCESS AUTOMATED EXTERNAL DEFIBRILLATOR PROGRAM PROVIDED
9 UNDER § 13–517 OF THE EDUCATION ARTICLE.
10 Article – Public Safety
11 2–101.
12 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
13 (g) (1) “Law enforcement agency” means a law enforcement agency of a
14 department, county, or municipal corporation of the State.
15 (2) “Law enforcement agency” includes:
16 (i) sheriffs; and
17 (ii) similar agencies of other states and the United States.
18 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
19 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
